data.title: 2024 Community Guide and Directory
data.text:
WELCOME

From the Partnership President

It is my pleasure to present Partnership Lake Houston’s 2023 Community Guide and Directory. Our goal is to create community, provide business resources, and operate as the leaders of economic development in the Lake Houston Area. By partnering with local organizations, we are able to provide valuable information to Partnership members, businesses and families looking to relocate in this dynamic area. Our community has so much to offer and our proximity to the Houston, Texas metro area comes as an added bonus.

The Lake Houston Area offers outstanding access to business opportunities, superior education, exceptional health care, abundant recreation, and a variety of quality entertainment shopping and dining venues. This is a thriving, vibrant community. Partnership Lake Houston is diligently working to continue building on our incredible foundation as a great place to work, live, play and flourish.

We focus the efforts of Partnership Lake Houston on developing a healthy economic climate for our businesses, whether it’s through attraction of new businesses, business retention, business expansion, small business development, advocating for the public infrastructure or addressing issues that affect our economy. Our focus is to develop and promote local businesses no matter the size. In doing so, we strive to attract economic development opportunities to enrich our community. Our fundamental role is to continuously improve the quality of life in the Lake Houston Area.

Please use this 2023 Community Guide and Directory to help us market the region and support our local member businesses for all of your shopping, product and service needs. We encourage you to support the many Partnership member firms in this guide. Feel free to contact us, if you have any questions or need additional information, about the Lake Houston Area or our organization.

Kyle Sheldon

President/CEO

Partnership Lake Houston

From the Board Chair

On behalf of the Partnership Lake Houston Board of Directors, staff and our 1,000 member businesses, welcome home.

The Lake Houston area is the hub for northeast Harris County, providing an unbeatable combination of location, economic opportunity, cultural diversity, accessibility to quality healthcare and education, and several of the most popular residential neighborhoods in the Houston market. Whether you are just passing through, new to the region, or have been a life-long resident, Partnership Lake Houston is here to serve you by bringing local businesses, the global economy and our community together.

As Partnership Lake Houston celebrates its 100th Anniversary as the pre-eminent business and civic organization in the area, it truly is an exciting time to be in Lake Houston. After several years of uncertainty and challenges, we as an organization and community have emerged on the other side stronger and better positioned to tackle the next 100 years. I invite you to check out any one of our numerous networking, educational or signature events and see for yourself the value in all that the Partnership has to offer including one-on-one support and engagement, promotion of local businesses of every size and advocacy for issues impacting you and your business.

I am proud to call this place home. Inside these pages, you’ll see the reason why with many of the people, places and businesses that make our community great. We’ve come a long way over the past 100 years – but in all reality, we’re just getting started.

Jason Stuebe

Chairman of the Board

AREA OVERVIEW

The Lake Houston Area’s proximity to the Gulf of Mexico provides mild to warm temperatures year-round, making the area the perfect place for outdoor living. Annually, the average high is 78°F and the average low is 60°F. The coldest month of the year is January, and the hottest month is August. The wettest month is June with an average of 11.3 days with at least 0.04 inches of precipitation.

The Lake Houston Area is in the northeast quadrant of the Houston Metropolitan area, just 20 miles north of Downtown Houston on Interstate 69. It includes Atascocita, Walden, Eagle Springs, The Groves, and Lake Shore; the City of Humble; Kingwood; Generation Park; Summer Creek, comprised of Summerwood and Fall Creek; and portions of East Montgomery County, including Oakhurst, Porter, New Caney, and Valley Ranch. These areas are currently experiencing robust population and economic growth.

The area encompasses approximately 100 square miles of land in northeast Harris County and is mostly forested. The region has proven to be a strong attraction to newcomers due to its natural beauty, the recreational opportunities of Lake Houston and the San Jacinto River, the proximity of Bush Intercontinental Airport and the Port of Houston and the quality of its many subdivisions. Abundant health care and exemplary schools add to the appeal, while developments such as Generation Park with HTX Surf expected opening Fall 2024 and a Biotechnology center set to launch in 2024; high-tech distribution center planned by IKEA; Life Science hub, entertainment, trails, and park projects are a few of the newest additions to Generation Park. Travel a bit further North and you will find Valley Ranch, and Grand Texas Theme Park ensuring the Lake Houston Area will continue to prosper for years to come.

Eleven lanes of Interstate 69 flow to and from Downtown Houston, including one HOV lane for multi-passenger vehicles. The Sam Houston Tollway allows motorists to quickly travel 13 miles from I-69 near George Bush Intercontinental Airport to just past US 90. The Grand Parkway, which spans east to west to connect I-45 and I-69. This 180-mile circumferential highway traverses seven counties in the Greater Houston area and is divided into 11 segments designated A through I-2 with segments D-I-2B already completed and open to traffic. Park and Ride lots at Townsend Boulevard in Humble and Lake Houston Parkway in Kingwood allow commuters to Downtown Houston and The Medical Center to park their cars and commute to their place of work comfortably in a Metro bus. As construction of the Grand Parkway continues as the fourth and largest loop around Houston, the Lake Houston Area will enjoy more connectivity to the city’s major thoroughfares and added mobility for our growing communities. Bush Intercontinental Airport, Houston’s primary airport is just five minutes from Humble. Rail service runs through the Lake Houston Area linking the region to the Port of Houston and Galveston.

During the past several years, the Lake Houston Area has experienced an uptick in commercial developments. The region is an ever-widening district of prosperous commerce and multi-community growth and has become the cornerstone of Northeast Houston.

The 2022 population of the Lake Houston Area was 294,414, up from a 2010 Census count of 225,357. The 2026 projection for population is 324,636, representing an increase of 1.9% annually from 2022-2026. Currently, the population is 49.6% male and 50.4% female. The median age of the LHA is 34.4 compared to the U.S. median age of 38.1. It is estimated that 11.8% of the population age 25 and over in this area had earned a Master’s, Professional or Doctorate Degree and 24% had earned a bachelor’s degree. In comparison, for the United States, it is estimated 12.3% of the population over 25 had earned a Master’s, Professional or Doctorate Degree, while 21.2% had earned a bachelor’s degree.

The household count in this area has increased from 76,382 in 2010 to 98,403 in the current year, a change of 1.7% annually. The 2026 projection of households is 108,000 a change 1.0% annually from the current year total.

In 2022, 69.9% of the 98,403 housing units in the area are owner occupied; 25.1% are renter occupied and 5% are vacant. In the United States, 54% of the housing units are owner occupied; 36% are renter occupied and 8.6% are vacant. In 2010, there were 81,971 housing units in the area; 88% were owner occupied, 25.2% renter occupied and 6.8% vacant. The annual rate of change in housing units since 2010 is 2.46%. Median home value of owner-occupied units in the area is $243,209, compared to a median home value of $203,378 for the U.S. The average worker in the Lake Houston Area earned annual wages of $54,894 as of 2022Q1. Average annual wages per worker increased 2.2% in the region over the preceding four quarters. For comparison purposes, annual average wages were $64,121 in the nation as of 2022Q2. The cost of living is 7.1% lower in the Lake Houston Area than the U.S. average.

Economic Development

The Partnership Lake Houston area is home to one of the fastest growing sections of the Houston Metro. Covering seven zip codes (77044, 77338, 77339, 77335, 77345, 77346 and 77369), what began as a small community located near the San Jacinto River has blossomed into an ever-widening area of prosperous commerce and multi-community growth. With over 300,000 residents, a talented workforce, as well as top rated education (Humble ISD, Lone Star and San Jacinto Junior Colleges), our access to major freeways and proximity to IAH, the Port of Houston and the world’s largest medical center make our area appealing to commercial developers and sites selectors.

Entertainment is plentiful in the Partnership Lake Houston area. With the recreation of Lake Houston and the San Jacinto River, beautiful golf courses and various parks, outdoor enthusiasts can find plenty to keep them busy. The Partnership Lake Houston area is also a popular destination for endless hours of indoor entertainment and great dining.

The Partnership Lake Houston (PLH) works to entice industrial and commercial companies to the area, along with expanding existing businesses. That means high-quality jobs for our residents and development of a true live, work and play community.

This past year, the Lake Houston area has seen an uptick in Life Sciences projects, largely due to the development of the Life Sciences Manufacturing Campus and a Biotech Training Center at Generation Park. Generation Park is a 4,300-acre master-planned environment unlike any other with the clear and simple goal of driving business performance for their clients. McCord Development took this a step further with the development of BioHub Two, a 45-acre master-planned biomanufacturing campus with for sale and for lease built-to-suite biomanufacturing, lab and office space in Generation Park. This campus offers multiple site configurations, providing flexibility for operations of all sizes.

BioHub Two is adjacent to the Nimble BioSpaces facility and NIBRT/San Jacinto College Biotech Training Center. NIBRT, the world’s premier life science manufacturing workforce training institute, is partnering with San Jacinto College to open a Biotech Training Center at Generation Park. The Global Partners Center will be the only facility of its kind for the southern and southwestern United States and will feature a state-of-the-art bioprocessing pilot plant operated in a realistic GMP simulated and operational manufacturing environment.

With world-leading research and development and access to the growing, untapped life sciences workforce, Houston is an ideal location for biomanufacturing. The combination of over 700 life science companies and the logistical benefits of being in the center of the country for easy access make Houston the strategic choice. With partners like McCord Development and San Jacinto college, the Lake Houston area has defined itself as one of five regions within the Houston footprint that have a life sciences presence and is ready to compete.

It is a great honor to serve as Partnership Lake Houston’s Chief Economic Development Officer. As a longtime area resident, there is no other place I would rather help cultivate. My focus is on developing a healthy economic climate for our businesses, no matter what size, whether it’s through attraction of new businesses, business retention and expansion, small business development, advocating for the public infrastructure or addressing issues that affect our community; every business deserves to have an equal opportunity to grow and thrive.

Formally, I spent 31 years at CenterPoint Energy and began my career in Economic Development over 18 years ago. You might say that I sort of “fell” into Economic Development, but soon learned that this was an industry I loved and wanted to retire from. In 2017, I received my certification in Economic Development (CEcD) and went on to support many of the Economic Development organizations in the Houston region. The Houston region has some of the best Economic Developers in the business and I was able to learn from the best during my tenure at CenterPoint Energy.

My plan was to retire from CenterPoint Energy, but what’s that old saying: If you want to make God laugh, make plans? In 2022, I took a leap of faith and left CenterPoint Energy to oversee the economic development efforts of the Lake Houston area. Wow! What a year it’s been! The community has been so inviting and supportive and I really feel at home here. Logistically, we are in a prime location with access to major freeways, IAH is in our backyard, not to mention we are just a stone’s throw away from the Port of Houston and the world’s largest medical center.

My goal is to make sure our story is told properly, and we get in front of the right audiences. There is something very exciting about helping a community prosper and grow and I believe we have big things in our future. I stand forever humbled in this opportunity.

Stephanie Wiggins

Chief Economic Development Officer

Partnership Lake Houston

EDUCATION MATTERS

Humble ISD

Humble Independent School District began over 100 years ago as Harris County Common School District No. 28 with a single one-room schoolhouse. Today, with 47 campuses, more than 48,000 students and over 7,000 employees, Humble ISD is nationally recognized for the outstanding education it offers to students. Humble ISD is the sixth fastest growing school district in Texas out of 1,020 districts, and is currently the 24th largest district in the state.

Humble ISD students have a long history of outperforming students in Texas and the nation. The district’s rating for 2022 is a B. In 2020, 26 students received National Merit Scholar recognition in the achievement, commended, semifinalist and finalist categories. On the 2019 SAT, our students scored 76 points above the average Texas student. On state-mandated academic assessment tests, Humble ISD students traditionally score among the highest in Texas. Also, results of college entrance exams show district students scoring well above state and national averages. Surveys indicate that approximately 85% of our students plan to continue their education following graduation.

The Humble ISD community has enjoyed a long and successful commitment to excellence in Texas education, owing in part to the support of our families and business partners. A perfect example of this close and dynamic relationship is the Humble ISD Education Foundation, created in 1999 with $46,000 in donations. Today, through the help of generous supporters, more than $16.25 million in funds has been raised to provide the innovative and enriching projects taking place in our classrooms every day.

A crowning achievement, the Insperity Humble ISD Observatory, houses four telescopes, a retractable roof, a teaching classroom and Internet capability. Humble ISD is one of a very few school districts in the United States to have its own observatory.

A quick overview of some of the special learning opportunities offered in Humble ISD includes:

• Gifted & Talented – Humble ISD’s GT programs begin in elementary school and continue into high school with Pre-AP, AP, IB, and Honors classes. The ultimate goal of the program is to provide experiences whereby students will be challenged academically, socially and emotionally to achieve their greatest potential to manage change and to have a sense of responsibility for self, school, community and society.

• International Baccalaureate – Our district began offering the International Baccalaureate Diploma Program at Humble High School in 2008-2009 as an alternative to Advanced Placement courses. The IB Diploma Program is a highly respected, highly credible educational program that prepares students for success beyond the classroom and is recognized by the world’s leading colleges and universities. IB courses offer a college-level curriculum with international-mindedness at the high school level. The IB Diploma Program is a two-year program that starts in the 11th grade, and IB exams are taken at the end of the senior year.

• Dual Credit – Humble ISD, in a longstanding partnership with Lone Star College Kingwood, continues to offer students opportunities to earn both high school and college credit for courses taken as part of our Dual Credit Program. This program offers high school students an opportunity to take challenging classes while paying a discounted fee for college credit hours that transfer to public universities in Texas.

• AVID (Advancement Via Individual Determination) – The AVID system has been in place at many of our middle and high schools since 2010. AVID targets students in the academic middle, who in most cases, would be the first in their families to attend college; these are students who are capable of completing a rigorous curriculum but are falling short of their potential. AVID places these students on the college track, requiring them to enroll in their school’s toughest courses, such as Honors and Advanced Placement®. To support them in the rigorous coursework, AVID students learn organizational and study skills, develop critical thinking, learn to ask probing questions, receive academic help from peers and college tutors, and participate in enrichment and motivational activities to make their college dreams reality.

• Guy M. Sconzo Early College High School – Imagine a school where you attend college while you are still in high school. Imagine a school where your dreams of tomorrow are started today – Sconzo Early College High School. In partnership with Lone Star College-Kingwood, Sconzo Early College High School is a small school where qualified students can earn both a high school diploma and an Associate’s degree or up to two years of credit toward a Bachelor’s degree.

• Distance Learning – Distance learning is being used by students to take advantage of opportunities to interact with experts, collaborate with others and go on virtual field trips. Homebound students can communicate with their teachers and classmates, and they can take online classes. Humble ISD became the first K-12 school district to win the Outstanding Commitment to Excellence and Innovation in Distance Learning Award (2008-2009). Previously, only colleges or universities won this honor.

• Mentoring – The AIM (Academic Individual Mentor) Program brings community volunteers to two Humble ISD middle schools to establish and pursue academic goals with at-risk students. The program received a 2010 Gold Award from the Texas Assn. for Partners in Education.

Spring ISD

The Spring Independent School District serves more than 35,000 pre-kindergarten through 12th-grade students in a diverse district located 20 miles north of central Houston.

Guided by its strategic plan, Every Child 2020, the district is preparing students for success in college, career and life. With literacy as the foundation for learning across all grade levels, the district offers academic programs that meet the needs of all learners. From high-quality early childhood programs to college preparation courses and career pathway exploration, there are programs and services designed to meet the needs of every Spring ISD student.

The district takes pride in always improving and evolving, including strengthening and expanding its special education and gifted and talented services as well as its award-winning performing and visual arts program to serve even more students. In addition to bilingual instruction and English as a Second Language programs, which have been well-established for many years, the district has added a dual language program at three elementary schools. An array of extracurricular opportunities, including UIL 16-6-A athletics and nationally recognized JROTC programs, encourage students to explore and pursue their interests.

The district currently has 38 campuses that include 26 pre-kindergarten through fifth-grade elementary schools, seven sixth- through eighth-grade middle schools and five ninth- through 12th-grade high schools. That number will change soon with the construction of several new facilities – including two middle schools, three ninth-grade centers and a state-of-the-art stadium that will serve the entire district – all funded by a bond referendum approved by voters in 2016.

Lone Star College- Kingwood

Like many businesses and educational institutions, Lone Star College-Kingwood is finding creative ways to provide top-notch services to its customers, i.e., students, amid the ever-changing pandemic. The college’s mission is student success. To achieve this, the institution offers courses and programs in various modalities (in-person, online and hybrid) to help students meet their educational and career goals.

LSC-Kingwood has two satellite facilities. The LSC-Atascocita Center, located on West Lake Houston Parkway, offers local access to academic services, general courses, workforce training and leisure learning. It is also the home for iSchool High School-Atascocita, a tuition-free public charter school. The LSC-Process Technology Center has state-of-the-art simulation equipment, a hands-on training unit, labs and classrooms for the process technology and instrumentation technology programs. It also offers general college courses.

LSC-Kingwood, satellite facilities include:

• Instrumentation Technology Program trains students to maintain, calibrate, troubleshoot, repair and replace process instruments. Graduates can work in the chemical process industry, including refineries, power generation and food and beverage. Info: http://www.lonestar.edu/InstrumentationTechnology-AAS.htm

• Continuing Education Division provides free GED and ESOL classes in person and online in English and Spanish. Additional available courses include certified medical assistant, medical billing and coding, dental assisting, bookkeeping (English and bilingual) and phlebotomy. These classes are not free; however, students could receive financial assistance. Info: www.lonestar.edu/adult-education

• TRIO SSS Grant provides academic support to ensure success for students listed as first-generation in college, income-limited, or have a disability through free programming. The target audience includes first-generation, low-income, students with disabilities, former foster care, early college, dual credit and continuing education. Info: http://www.LoneStar.edu/TRIO-Kingwood

• Community-focused events provide entertainment and necessary services for the public. Those activities include fine arts events (drama, music, arts, etc.), monthly food fairs, tax aid assistance, civic engagement events, career fairs and an affordable dental clinic. Info: www.LoneStar.edu/kingwood

Lone Star College-Kingwood is the educational institution of choice for nearly 12,000 students. The address is 20000 Kingwood Drive. For more information, register for a class, or schedule a tour, visit http://www.LoneStar.edu/kingwood or call (281) 312-1600.

San Jacinto College

Northeast Houston residents can enjoy the convenience of San Jacinto college’s fifth campus, San Jacinto College - Generation Park Campus.

Conveniently located off Beltway 8 at West Lake Houston Parkway and Lockwood Road, the Generation Park campus focuses on academic classes that transfer to four-year colleges and universities. Classes include eight-week and 16-week options in face-to-face, online and hybrid formats.

“We offer a variety of class times and modalities that allow students to complete their degree in a manner and pace that are comfortable to them,” Executive Director Dr. Destry Dokes said. “Students are also supported by our outstanding faculty in all classes.”

San Jacinto College provides many resources and university partnerships to simplify the transfer process for students.

Focusing on Academics, Workforce

Generation Park administrators have been working with local school districts and community stakeholders to develop a campus that offers both general academic courses and associate degrees. Dr. Dokes believes the campus’ diverse options will most attract students.

“I believe students will choose us because of our academic and STEM [science, technology, engineering and math] course offerings, course relevance and transferability, and innovative technology to accommodate various learning styles and student service needs,” he said.

Workforce training solutions resources and opportunities through collaborative partnerships are also a mission of SJC. Generation Park leaders work with established and emerging industry partners to determine how the campus can assist with professional development.

Looking Ahead

The Generation Park Campus opened its first instructional building in fall 2020: A 55,000-square-foot classroom building at the heart of the 57-acre master-planned campus. The campus will continue to grow, bringing high-quality, affordable education options to the college’s northeast service area. San Jacinto College offers financial aid and scholarships to help students achieve their goals within their budget. Educational planners and counselors also guide students on their path to transfer institutions. Start the enrollment process at www.sanjac.edu/steps-enroll.

For more information about Generation Park, visit www.sanjac.edu/generation-park. The campus is at 13455 Lockwood Road, Houston, TX 77044.

PLAY LAKE HOUSTON

Atascocita Park

Overseen by Precinct 3 Commissioner Tom Ramsey, the 21.2-acre Atascocita Park opened in 2020. The park includes one of the highest skywalks in the area, two separate dog parks, a large playground and picnic pavilion, walking trails, restroom facilities and open play areas for activities.

Hirsch Memorial Park

The 4-acre Humble Park features playground equipment, a gazebo, a swimming pool, picnic shelters, half-court basketball areas and two lighted tennis courts. Named after Jules Hirsch, “one of the most active members of the Houston community,” the park is beloved by many. Older Humble residents visiting the park still remember spending Friday nights dancing at the rec.

Jesse H. Jones Park & Nature Center

Natural beauty and history are combined in this 225-acre park located along the banks of Spring Creek. The park is home to a variety of plant and wildlife species, two authentic 1830s homestead reproductions, white sand beaches along Spring Creek and century-old cypress trees. All features are accessible by over eight miles of paved, handicap-friendly pedestrian trails and several unpaved trails. Point-to-point canoeing is permitted with advanced reservations and fishing is permitted following state laws and regulations.

Lake Houston Wilderness Park

Lake Houston Wilderness Park is the only park in the Houston Parks and Recreation Department system where overnight camping is available. With approximately 5,000 acres of forest, 12 miles of hiking and biking trails, eight miles of equestrian trails and camping facilities, the park offers a variety of activities for visitors to experience. Cabins and walk-in campsites are available for rent.

Lindsey Lyons Park and Sports Complex

An all-inclusive, barrier-free playground and special needs restroom facility for children of all physical abilities reside at the largest Precinct 3 Park. The playground features eight ground-level activities and 45 elevated play activities – 33 accessible by ramp and 43 accessible by transfer. The basketball, softball, football and soccer fields are located near a barbeque pavilion, an array of picnic tables and a paved walking trail.

Mercer Botanical Gardens

Mercer Arboretum and Botanical Gardens is a nationally recognized public garden showcasing the Gulf Coast region’s largest collection of native and cultivated plants. Spanning over 400 acres of land in Humble, the beautifully maintained gardens feature bamboo, color displays, daylilies, endangered species, herbs and more. Experienced horticulturists, botanists and gardeners are happy to provide information and share their knowledge as visitors walk through the park.

Schott’s Park

Covering 24 acres, Schott’s Park features many amenities including an open-air pavilion, softball field, hardball field, picnic shelters, a playground, a half-court basketball area and almost two miles of walking trails, offering workouts along the way. In late 2020, Schott’s Park started hosting a quarterly farmers market.

Timberwood Park

Timberwood Park covers three acres and is in the Timberwood subdivision of Humble. Timberwood Park is open from 8 a.m. until dusk. The park features playground equipment, two half-court basketball areas and picnic tables.

Uptown Park

Located in downtown Humble, Uptown Park features a stage, a gazebo, picnic tables and playground equipment. The park hosts an array of community events throughout the year, including outdoor concerts visited by many. This park is also known to host the infamous Humble “Good Oil Days” festival.

Edgewater Park

The newest Lake Houston area park features nature trails, picnic areas, a playground, restrooms and a public boat ramp. This park aids in flood mitigation efforts by preserving the area as green space, absorbing more water than surrounding developed areas, and slowing the rate of runoff during heavy rainfall.

Surrounding Area

The Greater Houston area offers an endless array of activities just a short distance away. Check out the Museum District, the Houston Zoological Gardens at Hermann Park, or Space Center Houston at NASA. Take in some history at the San Jacinto Monument and the Battleship Texas, enjoy premier shopping at The Galleria or search for bargains in the bohemian resale shops of The Heights. With more than 10,000 restaurants to choose from, you can try everything from world famous steakhouses and BBQ joints to unforgettable seafood fresh from the Gulf during the day before heading to Midtown, Rice Village or Washington for evening drinks. Head further south to Galveston Island to walk the Strand Historic District, Pleasure Pier and many public and private beaches across the island. Visit Moody Gardens or take the whole family to enjoy the rides, restaurants and seasonal entertainment at Kemah Boardwalk.

Partnership

Lake Houston

Photo courtesy of Kathleen Muhle

Our Mission: Promote businesses, enhance economic and community development, and serve as a catalyst for improving the overall quality of life in the Lake Houston Area.

Partnership Lake Houston

Since 2011, our chamber of commerce has been transitioning from a business network to an all-encompassing resource for businesses. After the destruction of Hurricane Harvey, Lake Houston leaders saw a need for the Chamber and Economic Development Partnership to merge for the benefit of all area businesses. Between the coordination of internal and external resources with businesses, agencies and organizations, the Partnership played a large part in rebuilding the Lake Houston area.

Today, the Partnership is thriving at an exponential rate and currently serves close to 1,000 members. We are focused on continuing to be the advocate for business and economic development in Lake Houston and surrounding areas.

Partnership Lake Houston strives to be a gateway where local business, global economy, and the quality of life come together. That vision is based on a foundation of five pillars:

• Being The Voice of Business

• Enable Economic Growth

• Deliver Value to Investors

• Advance Community Excellence

• Develop Organization Sustainability

Signature Events

Partnership Golf Classic

More than 200 golfers participate annually in the Partnership Golf Classic. This event provides an excellent opportunity to mix and mingle with leaders of the Lake Houston Area business community and promote your business.

Party Lake Houston

As the Partnership’s largest fundraiser of the year, “Party Lake Houston” is a popular annual gathering of Lake Houston Area professionals and the businesses they represent. Approximately 300 patrons will attend this event to enjoy dinner and drinks, accompanied by a number of fun activities, auctions and more.

Economic Development Annual Luncheon

The Economic Development Annual Luncheon invites top investors to outline the upcoming strategic plan and direction, review the current year’s progress, and recognize the Lake Houston area influential ‘eco dev’ partners.

Elected Officials Reception

The Elected Officials Reception recognizes and honors the local, state and federal elected officials who represent the Lake Houston Area. The annual event gives the business community a chance to have one-on-one conversations with constituents.

Legislative Trips

The Lake Houston Legislative Trips to Austin and Washington, D.C. provide an opportunity for members to see the government in action as they meet with state officials, legislators and agencies. Constituents will deliver the Partnership’s legislative agenda to legislators and attend pre-arranged meetings, tours, and other legislative activities.

Partnership Programs

BizCom Groups

BizCom Groups gather business executives, community leaders and professionals to share updates on local projects and community developments in their areas. These monthly events are held in the Atascocita, Humble, Kingwood and Summer Creek High Schools in partnership with Humble ISD.

Partnership 101

Partnership 101 is a program designed to educate new Partnership investors how to best utilize their membership benefits. Held quarterly, attendees are introduced to the Partnership staff, review membership levels, learn how-to-use “Members Only” tools of the Partnership Lake Houston website, and are educated about the upcoming year’s programs and events.

Seminar Series

Partnership seminars are innovative programs designed to address the business community’s specific needs. Topics range from current events to new business practices, to industry inside knowledge. Each seminar provides expert subject matter and helpful resources.

Monthly Membership Luncheons

Luncheons consist of program updates from the Partnership, industry expert speakers and special topic discussions. Previous luncheons include Economic Outlook, Teachers of the Year, State of the State, Business Awards, Focus on Federal Government, Honoring Our Heroes, and State of Health Care.

Leadership Lake Houston

Leadership Lake Houston was created to educate, develop and enhance emerging leaders within the community. A class of 20-25 individuals from local businesses and organizations attend eight full-day sessions to learn about the different sectors that make up the Lake Houston Area community and how to make an impact on the growth and vitality of the Lake Houston Area by successfully serving in leadership roles.

Leadership Lake Houston Alumni

Created by and for the Graduates of the Leadership Lake Houston Program, this association of growing community leaders meets for social events, service projects and continued educational opportunities. This group is for alumni who wish to continue leadership training and maintain the strong relationships built through the Partnership.

Networking After Hours

Networking After Hours attracts members to a local business after work to enjoy food and beverages with the opportunity to network and connect with other members. Held six times a year, this gathering not only allows new members to showcase their business to other Partnership members, but gives existing members an opportunity to strengthen relationships.

Top 4 Under 40 Awards

The Top 4 Under 40 Awards honors young, local entrepreneurs and business professionals whose work has made an impact in the Lake Houston Area.

Committees and Task Forces

Ambassadors

Ambassadors are dedicated investors that represent the Partnership at ribbon cuttings, open houses and networking events. Ambassadors seek to guide new members by forming mentorships.

Flood Resiliency Task Force

The purpose of the Flood Resiliency Task Force is to continue work to protect the Lake Houston Area by initiating and monitoring flood resiliency projects.

Public Affairs Committee

The Public Affairs Committee reviews, develops and supports issues that promote a positive, pro-business economy. This group collaborates with elected officials to establish regulations and policies that will improve the ability of area businesses to continue generating income and creating jobs.

Transportation Committee

The Transportation Committee works with transportation organizations and government officials to advance and improve mobility in the Lake Houston Area. The Committee educates businesses on proposed projects and solicits feedback.
